# Research job: {job_name}

## Goal
Lower `mean(|timing_offset_min|)` on the {dataset_slug} subset by editing
`params/research/{job_name}/current.json`. Lower is better.

## The loop
1. Form a hypothesis about which allowlisted parameter(s) to change and why.
2. Edit `current.json` (only keys matching the allowlist above).
3. Run: `python -m server.research iterate {job_name}`
   - Read stdout for `objective: <number>`.
4. If the new objective is **lower** than the current best:
   - Run: `python -m server.research validate {job_name}`
   - If `validation_objective` is also lower than the previous best
     validation, keep the edit and update your "current best" mental note.
   - If validation got *worse*, revert the edit (subset overfit) and note it.
5. If the objective got worse, revert `current.json` and try a different change.
6. Repeat until the wall-clock budget is exhausted.

## Joint multi-parameter search

Single-parameter probing is slow and gets stuck at coordinate-wise minima.
When you identify 2–6 coupled parameters that plausibly interact, hand them
to the built-in Nelder-Mead optimizer instead of grinding by hand:

```
python -m server.research search {job_name} \
    --params moon.start_pos,moon_def_a.speed,moon_def_a.start_pos \
    --budget 60
```

The search reads the current state of `current.json`, runs Nelder-Mead over
just the listed keys against the subset, and — only if it finds a strictly
better joint assignment — overwrites `current.json` with the best state.
If it doesn't improve, `current.json` is untouched. A single summary entry
is appended to `log.jsonl` with `kind: "search"` recording the starting
and best objectives and the number of evaluations used.

Guidelines for using `search`:
- **2–6 parameters at a time**, not all 48. More dimensions → exponentially
  harder search. Pick ones you have a coupling hypothesis about.
- **Don't mix highly-sensitive and insensitive parameters** in one search —
  the sensitive ones will dominate and the insensitive ones will barely move.
- **Budget ~10× the number of parameters** as a starting point. A 3-param
  search with budget=30–60 usually converges.
- **Always run `iterate` by hand first** to get the starting objective so
  you know whether the search's "improvement" is meaningful.
- **Validate after a successful search**, same as a hand edit — the search
  is still operating on the subset and can still overfit.

## Constraints
- **Only edit `current.json`.** Never touch `baseline.json`, `subset.json`,
  or any other file.
- **Only edit allowlisted keys.** The CLI will hard-fail if you don't.
- **One change at a time** (by hand) when possible — easier to attribute wins.
  For joint moves, use `search` instead of editing multiple fields manually.

## Background: the Tychos model (technical brief)

### Geometry
Tychos is a **geo-heliocentric** model. Earth sits near the system barycenter;
the Sun orbits Earth once per year (orbital diameter ~299.2 Mkm, speed ~107,226
km/h) and carries Mercury and Venus as its satellites. Mars, Jupiter, Saturn
and the outer planets orbit the Sun. Unlike a strict Tychonic model, Earth is
not perfectly static: it crawls along a large circular **"PVP" (Polaris-Vega-Polaris) orbit**
of diameter 113,230,656 km (radius ~56.6 Mkm) at ~1.6 km/h, completing one
revolution in **25,344 years** (the "Tychos Great Year"), opposite in sense to
the Sun. Because Earth simultaneously rotates (361°/solar day) and translates
along the PVP orbit, a body fixed to Earth traces a **prolate trochoid** — the
book calls this "man's yearly path" — and the combination produces the analemma
with its 3:1 asymmetry. The Moon orbits Earth on a ~763,095 km-diameter circle
at ~3,656 km/h (sidereal 27.322 d, synodic ~29.22 d, called the TMSP in the
book). Eclipses arise when the Moon's orbit crosses the Earth–Sun line in this
frame; the book itself does not give an explicit eclipse-mechanics derivation,
so the mechanism here is inferred from the pure geometry of moon + sun circles
around Earth.

### Parameter meanings (in Tychosium terms)
- **`orbit_radius`** — radius of the body's primary circle around its center.
  For `sun` this is ~1 AU; for `moon` ~381,547 km. A +1% change scales the
  whole trajectory outward and (for the Moon) proportionally shifts the
  geometric alignment window for eclipses, mainly affecting shadow geometry
  and separation, not mean timing.
- **`orbit_center_a/b/c`** — Cartesian offsets of the orbit's center from
  its parent. Non-zero values are how Tychosium encodes eccentricity-like
  displacements and epicyclic corrections; they tilt the line of apsides
  and create the asymmetry that mainstream models call eccentricity. A 1%
  change in an offset moves the apse line and modulates timing near syzygy
  by tens of seconds to a minute.
- **`orbit_tilt_a/b`** — two-axis inclination of the orbital plane relative
  to the parent frame. For the Moon this encodes the ~5° lunar inclination
  and nodal orientation. Timing sensitivity is weak; tilt mostly controls
  whether a given syzygy is an eclipse at all (separation at closest approach).
- **`start_pos`** — angular phase at t=0 (radians in the internal
  representation, degrees in the JSON). Pure phase offset along the orbit.
- **`speed`** — angular rate per Tychos time unit. Since `sun.speed = 2π`,
  the base time unit is one (Tychos) year; `moon.speed ≈ 2π · (365.25/27.322)`
  accordingly.

### Deferents
Tychosium layers smaller carrier circles ("deferents") on the primary orbit
to reproduce lunar/solar corrections without Keplerian ellipses:
- **`moon_def_a`** — the book explicitly discusses an **8.85-year apsidal
  precession of the Moon's perigee** (0.1114°/day, stated as a 3:1 ratio
  against Earth's PVP motion). `moon_def_a` is the carrier that rotates the
  moon's apse line on this cycle; its `speed` should correspond to 2π/8.85
  rad/yr. Tuning it changes the ±few-minute modulation of eclipse times on
  that period.
- **`moon_def_b`** — a second smaller deferent. The book links lunar
  **evection** to a ~31.8-day oscillation of ±1.274° producing ~14,070 km
  lateral displacement, attributed to the PVP geometry rather than
  perturbation theory. `moon_def_b` most plausibly encodes this evection-like
  correction; the book does not name this parameter directly, so the mapping
  is inferred from the geometry.
- **`sun_def`** — a deferent on the Sun's orbit encoding the solar
  equation-of-center analogue (what mainstream calls Earth's orbital
  eccentricity). It shifts the Sun's apparent longitude by up to ~±2° over
  the year.

### What moves eclipse timing vs. what doesn't
**High leverage on timing:**
- **`moon.start_pos`** — direct, linear leverage: the Moon sweeps ~0.549°/hr,
  so a 1° phase error ≈ **109 min of timing shift on every eclipse**.
  Highest-leverage parameter for a constant offset. Start here.
- **`moon.speed`** — produces a secular drift proportional to elapsed time;
  small error becomes large over 100-year baselines. Note: in v1-original/v1
  this appears to already be near a local minimum (empirically verified).
- **`moon_def_a`** (rate and phase) — modulates timing by a few minutes on
  the 8.85-yr perigee cycle; essential for fitting a multi-decade span.
- **`moon_def_b`** — evection-scale modulation (~±1 min, ~31.8-day period)
  relevant for per-event residuals.

**Medium leverage:**
- **`sun.start_pos`, `sun.speed`, `sun_def.*`** — set where the Sun is on
  the sky, so they affect the date of syzygy (and thus which new/full moons
  become eclipses) and the longitude of the shadow track. A 1° error in sun
  longitude shifts eclipse timing by about 2 hours via the Moon's catch-up
  rate (~12°/day synodic ≈ 2 hr/°). Non-trivial but smaller per-degree than
  `moon.start_pos`.
- **`sun.orbit_center_*` / `sun_def`** — encode the solar equation of
  center; errors here bias timing seasonally (max near the perihelion/
  aphelion analogue).

**Low / no leverage on timing:**
- **`earth.speed` (PVP rate)** — 25,344-year period. Over 100–200 years
  Earth moves only a few thousand km along the PVP arc, well under the
  Moon's orbit radius; effect on eclipse timing is **negligible**.
  **Empirically verified: a 40% change in `earth.speed` produced zero
  detectable change in the objective on a 20-event 1909–2100 subset.**
  Do not waste iterations probing it.
- **`moon.orbit_tilt_*`, `moon.orbit_radius`** — affect whether a syzygy
  lands on or near the ecliptic (i.e. whether it *is* an eclipse) and
  shadow geometry, but not when the closest approach happens. Expect
  movement in `mean_separation_arcmin` but little in `objective`.

### Time and sign conventions
The book itself does not specify a numerical epoch or timing sign convention.
From the codebase: catalog times are **Julian Date in TT**, and
**`timing_offset_min = (best_jd - catalog_jd) × 1440`**, so a **positive**
value means tychos predicts alignment **later** than the catalog. A
systematically positive mean signed offset means "shift the Moon forward
in its orbit so it reaches alignment sooner" → **decrease** `moon.start_pos`
(in degrees).

### Known empirical findings (from prior research sessions)
These are facts learned from hand-probing v1-original/v1 against the solar
eclipse catalog with a 6-hour search window. Take them as context, not
dogma — if your current base params differ, re-verify:
- **`earth.speed` is insensitive.** See above.
- **`moon.speed` sits near a local minimum** in v1 — moving it ±1e-4 made
  the objective worse in both directions.
- **`moon.start_pos` around 261.2°** has an optimum near 260.95° (−0.25°),
  lowering the objective by ~5 min on a 20-event subset.
- **`moon_def_a.speed` around 0.71015** responds to fine (~1e-5) positive
  adjustments with small improvements, but +1e-4 overshoots.
- **Residual structure after phase tuning shows a concave-down hump
  centered near 1950** with +150 to +190 min errors in 1944/1953/1963 and
  −105 to −109 in 1912/2044. No single parameter in the current allowlist
  fully reshapes this hump — it may be a model-structure limitation rather
  than a parameter-tuning target. Try **`search` with joint
  `{{moon.start_pos, moon_def_a.speed, moon_def_a.start_pos}}`** as a
  starting combo before reporting a structural limit.
